  "texts": [
    "If the unknown distribution of the real-world data is approximated by G (i.e.",
    "G * λ ≈ µ) and D is only able to guess the real-world from the fake samples (i.e.",
    "D(•) ≈ 1 2), the problem (3) reached its optimum.The training of a GAN is structured as a minmax game between the discriminator D and the generator G, which is mathematically represented by the min-max optimization problemmin G max D L(D, G) = min G max D E x∼µ [log(D(x))] + E z∼λ [log(1 -D(G(z)))].",
    "(3)Note that the loss function L(D, G) is commonly known as binary cross-entropy [94].",
    "As observed in [27], taking the maximum over a sufficiently large hypothesis space H D of discriminators yields to maxD∈H D L(D, G) = d JS (µ∥G * λ) + log(4),(4)where, d JS (µ∥G * λ) is the Jensen-Shannon (JS) divergence [95], which is an information-theoretic pseudodistance between the invariant measure µ and the generated measure G * λ and is defined asd JS (µ∥G * λ) = d KL µ G * λ + µ 2 + d KL G * λ G * λ + µ 2."
  ],
